'''Julian Nagelsmann''' (born 23 July 1987) is a German professional [[Association football manager|football coach]] who is currently the manager of [[Germany national football team|Germany]]. He has previously managed [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|TSG Hoffenheim]], [[RB Leipzig]] and [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in the [[Bundesliga]].

Born in [[Bavaria]], Nagelsmann retired as a footballer at age 20 after a succession of injuries. In 2010, he began his coaching career as a youth coach at TSG Hoffenheim, eventually coaching their first team in 2015, where he led them to a third-place finish in the [[Bundesliga]] and [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] qualification. He departed Hoffenheim in 2019 and was appointed at fellow Bundesliga club RB Leipzig, reaching the semi-finals of the UEFA Champions League in 2020.

Nagelsmann was appointed by Bayern Munich in 2021 for a world record managerial transfer worth €25 million (£21.7 million), making him the [[Transfer (association football)#Managers|most expensive manager ever]]. He won the [[Bundesliga]] title in his debut season, but was dismissed as manager from the club in March 2023.

In September 2023, he was appointed as the coach of the Germany national team.

==Early life==
Nagelsmann was born on 23 July 1987 in [[Landsberg am Lech]], [[Bavaria]]. He played for [[FC Augsburg]] and [[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]] at youth level,<ref name=":6">{{cite news |date=11 February 2016 |title=Hoffenheim appoint 28-year-old Julian Nagelsmann as head coach |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/feb/11/hoffenheim-appoint-julian-nagelsmann-youngest-coach |access-date=11 February 2016 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077|archive-date=13 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210213161407/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/feb/11/hoffenheim-appoint-julian-nagelsmann-youngest-coach |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="DW" /> and was the [[Captain (association football)|captain]] of Munich's U19 team.<ref name="sportmob">{{cite web |url=https://sportmob.com/en/article/970569-julian-nagelsmann-biography |title=Julian Nagelsmann Biography |publisher=Sport Mob |date=29 June 2021 }}</ref> In the 2006–07 season, he was part of the second team but made no appearances due to injuries. Nagelsmann returned to Augsburg for the 2007–08 season coached by [[Thomas Tuchel]], but injured his knee and meniscus for the second time, damaging the cartilage.<ref name="BBCNJ" /> As a result, he decided to end his footballing career at the age of 20.<ref name=":6" /><ref name="DW">{{cite news|last1=Dunbar|first1=Ross|title=Meet Hoffenheim's Julian Nagelsmann: the youngest coach in Bundesliga history|url=http://www.dw.com/en/meet-hoffenheims-julian-nagelsmann-the-youngest-coach-in-bundesliga-history/a-18808831|access-date=24 November 2015|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=27 October 2015|archive-date=27 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427123039/https://www.dw.com/en/meet-hoffenheims-julian-nagelsmann-the-youngest-coach-in-bundesliga-history/a-18808831|url-status=live}}</ref> He had already assisted his head coach Thomas Tuchel as a scout in the first half of 2008. He studied business administration in university for four semesters until he transferred to sports science.<ref name="DW"/> He then concentrated on coaching, returning to his former club 1860 Munich as an assistant to [[Alexander Schmidt (football manager)|Alexander Schmidt]] for Munich's U17 team from 2008 to 2010.<ref name=":6" />

==Coaching career==
===Early career===
Nagelsmann joined [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|TSG Hoffenheim]]'s youth academy in 2010 and coached different youth teams in the following years.<ref name="DW" /> He was an assistant coach during Hoffenheim's [[2012–13 TSG 1899 Hoffenheim season|2012–13 season]], and up until 11 February 2016, was coaching the club's U19 team.<ref name=":6" /> He coached Hoffenheim's U19 "junior team" to win the [[Under 19 Bundesliga#Bundesliga era|2013–14 Under 19 Bundesliga]] title.<ref name=":6" /> During his time as assistant coach, goalkeeper [[Tim Wiese]] nicknamed Nagelsmann "Mini-[[José Mourinho|Mourinho]]".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Krämer |first1=Christian |date=27 October 2015 |title=Künftiger Hoffenheim-Trainer: Wer ist dieser Julian Nagelsmann (28)? |url=http://www.spiegel.de/sport/fussball/tsg-1899-hoffenheim-wer-ist-dieser-julian-nagelsmann-a-1059820.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231135313/http://www.spiegel.de/sport/fussball/tsg-1899-hoffenheim-wer-ist-dieser-julian-nagelsmann-a-1059820.html |archive-date=31 December 2018 |access-date=24 November 2015 |language=de}}</ref>

===TSG Hoffenheim===
Nagelsmann was appointed head coach of TSG Hoffenheim on 27 October 2015. He was due to begin his tenure at the beginning of the [[2016–17 TSG 1899 Hoffenheim season|2016–17 season]].<ref name=":6" /><ref name="Hoffenheim appoint 28-year-old manager Julian Nagelsmann">{{cite news|title=Hoffenheim appoint 28-year-old manager Julian Nagelsmann|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34652888|access-date=25 November 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=27 October 2015|archive-date=31 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031103643/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34652888|url-status=live}}</ref> He was given a three-year contract.<ref name=":6" /> At the time of his appointment, Nagelsmann was 28, and the youngest coach in Bundesliga history.<ref name="DW"/><ref name="Hoffenheim appoint 28-year-old manager Julian Nagelsmann"/> He was to be the successor for [[Huub Stevens]], who had replaced [[Markus Gisdol]] the previous year.<ref name=":6" /> On 10 February 2016, Stevens resigned as head coach due to health problems, and Nagelsmann's tenure as head coach was brought forward by the Hoffenheim board a day later.<ref name="Hoffenheim unveil Julian Nagelsmann, youngest coach in Bundesliga history">{{cite news|last1=Dunbar|first1=Ross|title=Hoffenheim unveil Julian Nagelsmann, youngest coach in Bundesliga history|url=http://www.dw.com/en/hoffenheim-unveil-julian-nagelsmann-youngest-coach-in-bundesliga-history/a-19044699|access-date=12 February 2016|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=12 February 2016|archive-date=9 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709031456/https://www.dw.com/en/hoffenheim-unveil-julian-nagelsmann-youngest-coach-in-bundesliga-history/a-19044699|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2015–18: Avoiding relegation and Champions League qualification====
When Nagelsmann took over the club in February 2016, Hoffenheim were 17th in the table, 7 points from the safety of 15th spot and facing relegation.<ref name="BBCNJ">{{cite news|title=Julian Nagelsmann: Hoffenheim boss taking Bundesliga by storm|last1=Johnston|first1=Neil|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37888868|work=BBC Football|access-date=15 November 2016|archive-date=27 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427142822/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37888868|url-status=live}}</ref> Under Nagelsmann they avoided relegation by winning 7 of their remaining 14 matches and finished a point above the relegation playoff spot.<ref name=BBCNJ/>

Hoffenheim's good run of play continued in the [[2016–17 Bundesliga]] season, where they finished 4th in the table and qualified for the [[2017–18 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] qualifying phase for the first time in their history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bundesliga – Spieltag / Tabelle |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2016-17/0/0/spieltag.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408210753/http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2016-17/0/0/spieltag.html |archive-date=8 April 2019 |access-date=9 July 2018 |website=[[Kicker (magazine)|Kicker]] |publisher=kicker |language=de}}</ref>

On 9 June 2017, Hoffenheim extended the contract of Nagelsmann until 2021.<ref name="Nagelsmann extends contract as Hoffenheim head coach">{{cite news|title=Nagelsmann extends contract as Hoffenheim head coach|url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/julian-nagelsmann-has-extended-his-contract-as-hoffenheim-head-coach-until-2021-446276.jsp|access-date=11 June 2017|publisher=[[Bundesliga]]|date=9 June 2017|archive-date=9 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709031453/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/julian-nagelsmann-has-extended-his-contract-as-hoffenheim-head-coach-until-2021-446276.jsp|url-status=live}}</ref> In the Champions League play-off round, Hoffenheim lost to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] 6–3 on aggregate, then finished last in their [[2017–18 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] group with only one win against [[İstanbul Başakşehir F.K.|İstanbul Başakşehir]]. After finishing third in [[2017–18 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]], the club which had their best place in the league in their history managed to secure a direct qualification for the next Champions League season.

====2018–19: Final season====
In the [[2018–19 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], Nagelsmann became the youngest coach, aged 31 years and 58 days, to feature in the competition, doing so in the first group stage match against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/uefa-champions-league/champions-league-extra-time-julian-nagelsmann-becomes-comps-youngest-ever-manager/news-story/6b3c9b8f852ef24e2bda6e1162e8c860 |title=Champions League Extra Time: Julian Nagelsmann becomes comp's youngest ever manager |date=20 September 2018 |website=FOX SPORTS }}</ref> However, Hoffenheim finished last in their group with three draws and three defeats.

On 21 June 2018, Hoffenheim announced that Nagelsmann would be leaving the club at the end of the [[2018–19 TSG 1899 Hoffenheim season|2018–19 season]].<ref name="Bestätigt: Nagelsmann ab 2019 Trainer bei RB Leipzig">{{cite web |date=21 June 2018 |title=Bestätigt: Nagelsmann ab 2019 Trainer bei RB Leipzig |url=https://www.kicker.de/bestaetigt_nagelsmann-ab-2019-trainer-bei-rb-leipzig-726090/artikel |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621213626/http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/726090/artikel_bestaetigt_nagelsmann-ab-2019-trainer-bei-rb-leipzig.html |archive-date=21 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |website=[[Kicker (magazine)|Kicker]] |publisher=kicker |language=de}}</ref><ref name="Julian Nagelsmann: Hoffenheim coach to join RB Leipzig after 2018-19 season">{{cite web |title=Julian Nagelsmann: Hoffenheim coach to join RB Leipzig after 2018–19 season |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44568627 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=9 July 2018 |date=21 June 2018 |archive-date=27 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427142827/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44568627 |url-status=live }}</ref> He oversaw his 100th league game as Hoffenheim coach on 19 January 2019, in a 3–1 defeat to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]. In doing so, he became the youngest Bundesliga coach to reach the 100 match milestone.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/hoffenheim-bayern-munich-live-line-ups-stats-james-rodriguez-ribery-alphonso-davies-2884-1452|title=Leon Goretzka double helps Bayern Munich down Hoffenheim|publisher=Bundesliga|date=19 January 2019|access-date=20 January 2019|archive-date=22 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200922004846/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/hoffenheim-bayern-munich-live-line-ups-stats-james-rodriguez-ribery-alphonso-davies-2884-1452|url-status=live}}</ref>

===RB Leipzig===
On 21 June 2018, [[RB Leipzig]] announced that Nagelsmann would be their coach from the [[2019–20 RB Leipzig season|2019–20 season]] and he signed a four-year contract which would expire in 2023.<ref name="Bestätigt: Nagelsmann ab 2019 Trainer bei RB Leipzig"/><ref name="Julian Nagelsmann: Hoffenheim coach to join RB Leipzig after 2018-19 season"/>

====2019–20: Champions League semi-final====
[[File:2019-07-12 Fußball; Freundschaftsspiel RB Leipzig - FC Zürich 1DX 1124 by Stepro (cropped).jpg|thumb|Nagelsmann coaching [[RB Leipzig]] in 2019]]
Nagelsmann won his first Bundesliga match as RB Leipzig coach against [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]] 4–0,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/matchday/2019-2020/1|title=Bundesliga {{!}} Matchday 1 {{!}} Season 2019–2020|website=bundesliga.com – the official Bundesliga website|language=en|access-date=10 December 2019|archive-date=27 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427141322/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/matchday/2019-2020/1|url-status=live}}</ref> he also led Leipzig to a 1–1 draw against Bayern Munich.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/matchday/2019-2020/4|title=Bundesliga {{!}} Matchday 4 {{!}} Season 2019–2020|website=bundesliga.com – the official Bundesliga website|language=en|access-date=10 December 2019|archive-date=27 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427141327/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/matchday/2019-2020/4|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 17 September 2019, Nagelsmann became the youngest coach, aged 32 years and 56 days, to win a Champions League match, doing so in a 2–1 away win against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the first group stage match. On match-day 10, Leipzig won against [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz]] 8–0. Nagelsmann faced his former club Hoffenheim on match-day 14 and won 3–1 against them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/matchday/2019-2020/10|title=Bundesliga {{!}} Matchday 10 {{!}} Season 2019–2020|website=bundesliga.com – the official Bundesliga website|language=en|access-date=10 December 2019|archive-date=3 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103121912/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/matchday/2019-2020/10|url-status=live}}</ref>

After finishing top of their group, RB Leipzig reached the [[2019–20 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League knockout phase]] for the first time in their history. On 10 March 2020, following Leipzig's 4–0 win against [[José Mourinho]]'s [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], Nagelsmann became the youngest coach ever to win a UEFA Champions League knockout tie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/champions-league/1240370/nagelsmann-praises-rb-leipzig-for-sticking-to-style-in-tottenham-win/|title=Nagelsmann praises RB Leipzig for sticking to style in Tottenham win|date=11 March 2020|website=FOX Sports Asia|language=en-US|access-date=11 March 2020|archive-date=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311135826/https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/champions-league/1240370/nagelsmann-praises-rb-leipzig-for-sticking-to-style-in-tottenham-win/|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 13 August, RB Leipzig defeated Spanish side [[Atlético Madrid]] 2–1 in the quarter-finals, making Nagelsmann the youngest coach to ever progress to the Champions League semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53730258 |title=RB Leipzig 2–1 Atlético Madrid |website=BBC Sport |date=13 August 2020 |access-date=13 August 2020 |archive-date=19 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201119170749/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53730258 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":5" />

On 18 August, RB Leipzig played against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] in the Champions League semi-finals, where Nagelsmann faced his former boss during his time at Augsburg, Thomas Tuchel. However, RB Leipzig lost 3–0 to Paris Saint-Germain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53759778|title=RB Leipzig 0–3 Paris Saint Germain|language=en-GB|work=BBC Sport|date=18 August 2020|access-date=18 August 2020|archive-date=4 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200904130058/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53759778|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2020–21: DFB-Pokal runner-up====
In the 2020–21 season, RB Leipzig reached the round of 16 in the [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] to be eliminated by Liverpool, finished second in the Bundesliga and lost the [[2021 DFB-Pokal Final|DFB-Pokal Final]] 4–1 against [[Borussia Dortmund]].<ref name=":4">{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/borussia-dortmund-teach-rb-leipzigs-nagelsmann-a-lesson-in-german-cup-triumph/a-57514286-0 |title=Borussia Dortmund teach RB Leipzig's Nagelsmann a lesson in German Cup triumph |website=DW |date=14 May 2021 |access-date=22 May 2021 |archive-date=22 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210522195546/https://www.dw.com/en/borussia-dortmund-teach-rb-leipzigs-nagelsmann-a-lesson-in-german-cup-triumph/a-57514286-0 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Bayern Munich===
On 27 April 2021, Bayern Munich appointed Nagelsmann as head coach on a five-year deal, effective from 1 July 2021, replacing [[Hansi Flick]] for a [[Transfer (association football)#Managers|world record]] managerial transfer fee of €25 million.<ref name=":1">{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2021/04/julian-nagelsmann-to-become-fc-bayern-head-coach---hansi-flick%E2%80%99s-contract-terminated-as-requested |publisher=[[FC Bayern Munich]] |accessdate=27 April 2021 |date=27 April 2021 |title=Julian Nagelsmann to become new FC Bayern head coach}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{cite web|date=27 April 2021|title=Julian Nagelsmann to leave RB Leipzig at the end of the 2020/21 season|url=https://www.dierotenbullen.com/en/news/articles/2020-21-season/Julian-Nagelsmann-departure.html|url-status=live|access-date=27 April 2021|archive-date=27 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210427085408/https://www.dierotenbullen.com/en/news/articles/2020-21-season/Julian-Nagelsmann-departure.html}}</ref><!-- Empty reference <ref name=":8" /--><ref name=":9">{{cite web|date=27 April 2021|title=Introducing Julian Nagelsmann: The most expensive coach in football history|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/bundesliga/2021/04/27/6088554746163fa05b8b45d0.html|url-status=live|access-date=6 August 2021|archive-date=5 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210905105059/https://www.marca.com/en/football/bundesliga/2021/04/27/6088554746163fa05b8b45d0.html}}</ref>

====2021–22: First Bundesliga and DFL-Supercup titles====
Nagelsmann's first competitive match was a 1–1 draw against [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] in the [[Bundesliga]].<ref name="2021–22 season">{{cite web |title=Bayern München — Termine |url=https://www.kicker.de/fc-bayern-muenchen/spielplan/bundesliga/2021-22 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210829060039/https://www.kicker.de/fc-bayern-muenchen/spielplan/bundesliga/2021-22 |archive-date=29 August 2021 |access-date=29 August 2021 |website=[[Kicker (magazine)|Kicker]] |publisher=Olympia Verlag |language=de}}</ref> In Nagelsmann's first win with Bayern, he won his first title as a coach in Bayern's 3–1 victory over Borussia Dortmund in the [[2021 DFL-Supercup]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|title=Bayern Munich's Julian Nagelsmann eyes first title in Supercup clash with Dortmund {{!}} DW {{!}} 16 August 2021|url=https://www.dw.com/en/bayern-munich-julian-nagelsmann-borussia-dortmund-first-title/a-58877023|access-date=18 August 2021|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|archive-date=18 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210818031611/https://www.dw.com/en/bayern-munich-julian-nagelsmann-borussia-dortmund-first-title/a-58877023|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":3" />

On 24 August 2021, Nagelsmann led Bayern to a 12–0 victory against [[Bremer SV]] during the first round of the [[2021–22 DFB-Pokal]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|date=25 August 2021|title=Bayern put 12 past Bremer SV in cup win|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58335764|access-date=11 October 2021|archive-date=15 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211015115801/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58335764|url-status=live}}</ref> The scoreline was their biggest win in 24 years, since their 16–1 victory against [[DJK Waldberg]] in the DFB Cup in August 1997.<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite web|date=26 August 2021|title=Half a dozen facts about 12-0 at Bremer SV|url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2021/08/half-a-dozen-facts-about-the-12-0-at-bremer-sv|url-status=live|access-date=11 October 2021|website=FC Bayern|publisher=Bayern Munich|archive-date=26 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211026204716/https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2021/08/half-a-dozen-facts-about-the-12-0-at-bremer-sv}}</ref>

On 12 April 2022, Nagelsmann and his team were knocked out of the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] quarter-finals, 2–1 on aggregate by [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]],<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Carr |first=Damon |title=Breaking: Villarreal Knock Bayern Munich Out Of The Champions League Quarter-Final To Set Up Meeting With Either Liverpool Or Benfica |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/liverpool/news/a-late-goal-for-villareal-sees-them-knock-out-bayern-munich-in-the-champions-league |access-date=13 April 2022 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |archive-date=13 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220413031650/https://www.si.com/soccer/liverpool/news/a-late-goal-for-villareal-sees-them-knock-out-bayern-munich-in-the-champions-league |url-status=live }}</ref> and on 23 April, he won his second title, his first Bundesliga title, with three matches to spare.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bayern's Nagelsmann relieved with title after difficult first season |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/bayerns-nagelsmann-relieved-with-title-after-difficult-first-season-2022-04-23/ |access-date=8 May 2022 |work=Reuters |date=23 April 2022 |archive-date=8 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220508143445/https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/bayerns-nagelsmann-relieved-with-title-after-difficult-first-season-2022-04-23/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2022–23: Second DFL-Supercup title and mid-season sacking====
[[File:2022-07-30 Fußball, Männer, DFL-Supercup, RB Leipzig - FC Bayern München 1DX 3204 by Stepro.jpg|thumb|right|Nagelsmann with Bayern Munich in July 2022]]
On 30 July 2022, Nagelsmann won his second [[2022 DFL-Supercup|DFL-Supercup]] title after a 5–3 win over his former club RB Leipzig.<ref>{{cite news |title=RB Leipzig 3-5 Bayern Munich: Sadio Mane off the mark as five different scorers help Bayern retain Supercup |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11890/12662507/rb-leipzig-3-5-bayern-munich-sadio-mane-off-the-mark-as-five-different-scorers-help-bayern-retain-supercup |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230326012416/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11890/12662507/rb-leipzig-3-5-bayern-munich-sadio-mane-off-the-mark-as-five-different-scorers-help-bayern-retain-supercup |date=30 July 2022 |archive-date=26 March 2023 |access-date=26 March 2023 |work=Sky Sports |language=en-GB}}</ref> Later on, he managed to win all group stage matches in the [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] for the second consecutive season, beating top clubs such as [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] and [[Inter Milan]], to reach 14 consecutive victories in that round, 12 wins with Bayern and 2 with RB Leipzig; hence, equalling a record previously held by [[Louis van Gaal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2022/10/fc-bayern-set-new-ucl-record-with-plzen-win |title=FC Bayern set new Champions League record |website=FC Bayern Munich |date=13 October 2022 }}</ref> In the Champions League round of 16, Nagelsmann led Bayern to defeat Paris Saint-Germain 3–0 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/matches/profis/champions-league/2022-2023/fc-bayern-muenchen-paris-saint-germain-07-03-2023/report |title=Bayern see off PSG to reach Champions League quarters |publisher=Bayern Munich |date=8 March 2023 }}</ref>

On 24 March 2023, during the international break after a 2–1 defeat against [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]], Nagelsmann, who was on a skiing holiday in Austria,<ref>{{cite web |date=24 March 2023 |title=How Bayern Munich BRUTALLY ditched Julian Nagelsmann while he was on skiing holiday - and didn't even tell him! |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/how-bayern-munich-brutally-ditched-julian-nagelsmann-skiing-holiday/blt193d351b0c506954 |access-date=25 March 2023 |website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> was sacked by Bayern, with the club one point behind Dortmund in the [[2022–23 Bundesliga|league]], and was replaced by his former Augsburg coach Thomas Tuchel.<ref>{{cite web |date=24 March 2023 |title=Nagelsmann gefeuert, Tuchel wird Bayern-Trainer! |url=https://www.bild.de/sport/fussball/bayern-muenchen/fc-bayern-feuert-nagelsmann-83311920.bild.html |publisher=Bild |language=de}}</ref> The decision was taken by Bayern CEO [[Oliver Kahn]] and sporting director [[Hasan Salihamidžić]] in consultation with club president [[Herbert Hainer]].<ref name="FCBayernEndOfficial">{{cite web |title=FC Bayern and Julian Nagelsmann part company – Thomas Tuchel new head coach |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2023/03/fc-bayern-and-julian-nagelsmann-part-company---thomas-tuchel-new-head-coach |publisher=[[FC Bayern Munich]] |access-date=24 March 2023 |date=24 March 2023 |archive-date=24 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230324170921/https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2023/03/fc-bayern-and-julian-nagelsmann-part-company---thomas-tuchel-new-head-coach |url-status=live}}</ref> Kahn mentioned that fluctuations in performance following the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] prompted the decision, taking into consideration the objectives set for the current season and beyond.<ref name="FCBayernEndOfficial" /> The sack came ahead of [[Der Klassiker]] encounter against Dortmund in Bundesliga, [[2022–23 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]] quarter-final match against [[SC Freiburg|Freiburg]], and Champions League quarter-final fixtures against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite web |date=24 March 2023 |title=Kommentar zur Freistellung von Julian Nagelsmann beim FC Bayern: Oliver Kahns gefährliches Spiel mit der Zukunft |url=https://www.eurosport.de/fussball/bundesliga/2022-2023/kommentar-zum-fc-bayern-beben-um-julian-nagelsmann-oliver-kahns-gefahriches-spiel-mit-dem-feuer_sto9527782/story.shtml |publisher=Eurosport |language=de}}</ref>

Nagelsmann ended his tenure at Bayern with a 71.4% win rate, with only [[Pep Guardiola]], Hansi Flick and [[Carlo Ancelotti]] averaging more Bundesliga points than him.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/why-bayern-munich-sacked-julian-nagelsmann |title=Why Bayern Munich sacked Julian Nagelsmann |publisher=90min.com |date=24 March 2023 }}</ref>

===Germany===
On 22 September 2023, Nagelsmann was appointed as the new head coach of the [[Germany men's national football team|Germany national team]] ahead of [[UEFA Euro 2024]], which Germany was set to host, replacing [[Hansi Flick]] and signed a contract until July 2024. He became Germany's second-youngest coach at 36 years old, only behind [[Otto Nerz]], who was 34 when hired in 1926.<ref>{{cite web |date=22 September 2023 |title=Julian Nagelsmann ist neuer Fußball-Bundestrainer |url=https://www.dw.com/de/julian-nagelsmann-ist-neuer-fu%C3%9Fball-bundestrainer/a-66863002 |publisher=DW}}</ref> In April 2024, Nagelsmann extended his contract until the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |date=19 April 2024 |title=Bundestrainer Nagelsmann verlängert Vertrag bis zur WM 2026 |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/bundestrainer-nagelsmann-verlaengert-vertrag-bis-zur-wm-2026-260748/ |publisher=dfb.de}}</ref> In their European Championship group, Germany were paired with [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=UEFA.com |title=UEFA EURO 2024 final tournament draw |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/draws/ |access-date=7 July 2024 |website=[[UEFA]] |language=en}}</ref> In the opening match of Euro 2024, on 14 June, he became the [[UEFA European Championship records and statistics#Coaching|youngest to ever coach]] in the UEFA European Championship final tournament, aged just 36 years and 327 days.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/025f-0fd28e1a592d-c389509c8b2d-1000--euro-coaches-oldest-youngest-most-appearances-most-wins/ |title=EURO coaches: Oldest, youngest, most appearances, most wins |website=[[UEFA]] |publisher=[[Union of European Football Associations]] |date=13 June 2024 |access-date=14 June 2024 }}</ref> With 5–1 and 2–0 wins over Scotland and Hungary respectively,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Glendenning |first=Barry |date=19 June 2024 |title=Germany 2-0 Hungary: Euro 2024 – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2024/jun/19/germany-v-hungary-euro-2024-live-scores |access-date=7 July 2024 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Germany progressed to the Round of 16, where they faced [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]. Germany won 2–0, with a goal from [[Jamal Musiala]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=29 June 2024 |title=Germany beats Denmark 2-0 to advance to Euro 2024 quarterfinals after storm stops play |url=https://apnews.com/article/germany-denmark-euro-2024-b9d346ab4cb92b2d6e829091de65258b |access-date=7 July 2024 |website=AP News |language=en}}</ref> after a thunderstorm disrupted play. They faced eventual champions [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in the quarter finals. Germany lost 1–2 in [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]] to a 119th minute goal.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ronay |first=Barney |date=5 July 2024 |title=Spain show their steel to flatten Germany’s hopes in brutal spectacle |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jul/05/spain-prosper-after-weathering-germanys-storm-of-aggression |access-date=7 July 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

Subsequently, he guided his team to secure a spot in the [[2025 UEFA Nations League Finals]], finishing first in their group.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/uefa-nations-league-quarter-semi-final-draw-germany-29770 |title=UEFA Nations League: Germany to face Italy in the quarter-finals |publisher=Bundesliga |date=22 November 2024 }}</ref> In January 2025, Nagelsmann extended his contract until [[UEFA Euro 2028]].<ref>{{cite web |date=25 January 2025 |title=Bundestrainer Nagelsmann verlängert Vertrag bis 2028 |url=https://www.deutschlandfunk.de/bundestrainer-nagelsmann-verlaengert-vertrag-bis-118.html |publisher=Deutschlandfunk |language=de}}</ref>

==Style of management==
Nagelsmann is known for his versatility with formations, maintaining possession, and implementing ''[[gegenpressing]]'', whereby the team, after losing possession, immediately attempts to win back possession, rather than falling back to regroup. He was considered to be one of the best young managers in world football in 2021.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|title=Julian Nagelsmann: 10 things on Bayern Munich's record-breaking new coach|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/julian-nagelsmann-10-things-on-bayern-munich-s-coach-rb-leipzig-baby-mourinho-5300|access-date=19 December 2021|website=bundesliga.com - the official Bundesliga website|language=en|archive-date=19 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211219164744/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/julian-nagelsmann-10-things-on-bayern-munich-s-coach-rb-leipzig-baby-mourinho-5300|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=LKChuggz|date=10 November 2021|title=Julian Nagelsmann wants to see more Gegenpressing from his midfielders|url=https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2021/11/10/22773185/bayern-munich-analysis-julian-nagelsman-gegenpressing-joshua-kimmich-leon-goretzka-corentin-tolisso|access-date=19 December 2021|website=Bavarian Football Works|language=en|archive-date=19 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211219164741/https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2021/11/10/22773185/bayern-munich-analysis-julian-nagelsman-gegenpressing-joshua-kimmich-leon-goretzka-corentin-tolisso|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=The Bosses: Julian Nagelsmann, the managerial prodigy leading RB Leipzig's revolution|url=https://www.internationalchampionscup.com/the-bosses-julian-nagelsmann-the-managerial-prodigy-leading-rb-leipzigs-revolution|access-date=19 December 2021|website=www.internationalchampionscup.com|archive-date=19 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211219164743/https://www.internationalchampionscup.com/the-bosses-julian-nagelsmann-the-managerial-prodigy-leading-rb-leipzigs-revolution|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Personal life==
When he was just 20, Nagelsmann lost his father to [[suicide]]. Nagelsmann's father worked for the [[Federal Intelligence Service|Foreign Intelligence Service of Germany]] in a position unknown to his family.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Buschmann |first=Rafael |last2=Pfeil |first2=Gerhard |date=23 February 2024 |title=National coach Nagelsmann on his father in the secret service: "Even my grandfather believed his son was a soldier." |url=https://www.spiegel.de/sport/julian-nagelsmann-selbstzweifel-kenne-ich-eigentlich-nicht-a-9f2ba72e-56f8-4823-8084-9fd25f6c7ea0 |access-date=20 March 2025 |work=Der Spiegel |language=de |issn=2195-1349}}</ref>

Nagelsmann married his childhood sweetheart Verena,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Julian Nagelsmann Wife - Verena Nagelsmann |url=https://ohmyfootball.com/news/834/nagelsmann-wife-verena-nagelsmann |access-date=19 December 2021 |website=ohmyfootball.com |date=14 September 2021 |language=en |archive-date=19 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211219164741/https://ohmyfootball.com/news/834/nagelsmann-wife-verena-nagelsmann |url-status=live}}</ref> with whom he has two children, in 2018.<ref name="sportmob" /> The couple split in 2023, when it was revealed he was in a relationship with Lena Wurzenberger, a 30-year-old sports reporter for Germany's biggest newspaper, ''[[Bild]]''.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marieschultebockum/2023/03/24/bayern-munichs-60-million-dollar-fiasco-3-reasons-nagelsmann-was-fired/?sh=3d5c628a2397 | title=Julian Nagelsmann leaves wife | newspaper=Forbes | date=March 2023 | access-date=24 March 2023 }}</ref> In March 2023, Wurzenberger resigned from her work at ''Bild'', following Nagelsmann's dismissal from his job at Bayern.<ref>{{cite web |date=24 March 2023 |title=Nagelsmann-Freundin kündigt |url=https://www.sport1.de/news/mehr-sport/2023/03/fc-bayern-nagelsmann-freundin-wurzenberger-kundigt-bei-der-bild |publisher=Sport1 |language=de}}</ref>

==Outside football==
Nagelsmann played ice hockey for [[EV Landsberg]] for three years, and SV Apfeldorf during his time at Augsburg.<ref>{{cite web |date=10 January 2021 |title="Auf der Insel der Glückseligen" |url=https://www.kreisbote.de/sport/lokalsport/landsberg/interview-julian-nagelsmann-ueber-privilegien-des-fussballs-und-was-nach-leipzig-kommt-90160869.html |publisher=Kreisbote |language=de}}</ref> He enjoys mountain biking, skiing,<ref name="sportmob"/> and skateboarding.<ref>{{cite web |date=27 September 2021 |title=Nagelsmann kommt mit ungewöhnlichem Gefährt zum Bayern-Training - Lässiges Bild aufgetaucht |url=https://www.tz.de/sport/fc-bayern/fc-bayern-muenchen-julian-nagelsmann-skateboard-training-saebener-strasse-foto-zr-91000715.html |publisher=tz.de |language=de}}</ref> He is a [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]].<ref>{{cite news |date=April 2022 |title=FC Bayern: Ernährung - deshalb ist Julian Nagelsmann nun Vegetarier |url=https://www.welt.de/sport/fussball/bundesliga/article237927447/FC-Bayern-Ernaehrung-deshalb-ist-Julian-Nagelsmann-nun-Vegetarier.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220429092514/https://www.welt.de/sport/fussball/bundesliga/article237927447/FC-Bayern-Ernaehrung-deshalb-ist-Julian-Nagelsmann-nun-Vegetarier.html |archive-date=29 April 2022 |access-date=29 April 2022 |newspaper=Die Welt}}</ref>

